	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Wed, Mar 14th 12:13 PM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Good<span id=notbold>[4.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Hi.<br><br>I'm a lvl 26 Chantress, who's yet to get her AOE mez spell.&nbsp;&nbsp;I've found that the best way to play a chanter is to: A. Find an incredible group. This is ESSENTIAL.  Many, many people do not know how to group with enchanters, and as a result, the chanter uses all mana trying to keep the mobs off, and usually dies in the process (and most of the time, is the ONLY member of the party that dies).  This makes leveling up VERY hard to do, and causes a LOT of frustration.<br><br>B. After you find a group (or even two or three members. One preferably a tank with a NICE taunt level), make sure the group picks the leader, and ALL understand to make an /assist macro.  Stand back, listen for the leader to call out who he/she is attacking, and then begin to mez, one at a time the others.  Make sure your party understands that you, and they make take some hits, but it's nothing that can't be handled.  If the mob comes after you, ALWAYS have your color series memorized. This will BUY you time to get the mez off.  After all have been mezzed, target the one you mezzed first, and sit down and meditate. This will keep your mana up, and you ready for any other potential trains being caused.<br><br>If you have a high mana level, and there are only 2-3 mobs around, you can then spend some time debuffing, as this does not break mez.  Make sure your tanks know to ALWAYS taunt at least two times before breaking mez, or that mob will come after you, or your healer.<br><br>I hope this helps.<br><br>Selara<br>Tholuxe Paells<br>Lvl 26 Enchantress<br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 >&nbsp;</td><td align=right valign=bottom>
	   <span style='font-weight: normal; font-size: 9px;'>[<a href=#top>Top</a>]</span></tr>
